Parent-basename matching for non-dir patterns
For non-dir patterns (e.g., build) you also treat a file as matched when any parent directory basename matches the pattern (to emulate “ignore the directory implies ignore its contents”). That’s pragmatically fine, but it subtly differs from Git’s notion that the file itself isn’t matched by build; it’s ignored because an ancestor dir is ignored. Your parentExcluded guard likely prevents mis-reinclusions, but a couple of targeted tests will ensure no surprises when negations shuffle around.

** zero-segment behavior
Correct parity depends on whether a/** matches a (zero segments). doublestar treats ** as “zero or more segments”; Git’s wildmatch also allows zero in many positions, but discrepancies tend to hide here. Your data/** scenarios strongly imply the intended behavior, but add an explicit assertion to lock it (see tests below).

Braces inside character classes
You globally escape {/}, including when they appear in [...]. That should be harmless (both literal either way), but because it’s a transformation outside doublestar, it’s worth a couple of focused cases to ensure we never regress on odd parser interactions.

Excluding dirs via content patterns
Your first pass excludes directories for patterns like ** or rooted /* (and correctly skips */ content-only). This is deliberate, but “does abc/** exclude the abc dir entry itself in the parent map?” is library-behavior-dependent. Tests make it explicit.

